</div>
<p>The <b>whinchat</b> (<i>Saxicola rubetra</i>) is a small <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird_migration" title="Bird migration">migratory</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passerine" title="Passerine">passerine</a> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bird" title="Bird">bird</a> breeding in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Europe" title="Europe">Europe</a> and western <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asia" title="Asia">Asia</a> and wintering in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Africa" title="Africa">Africa</a>.</p>
<p>Its <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_name" title="Scientific name" class="mw-redirect">scientific name</a> means "small rock-dweller", in reference to its <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habitat" title="Habitat">habitat</a>. <i>Saxicola</i> derives from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title="Latin">Latin</a> <i>saxum</i> ("rock") + <i>incola</i> ("dwelling"); <i>rubetra</i> is a Latin term for a small bird.<sup id="cite_ref-Urquhart_2-0" class="reference"><a href="Saxicola_rubetra#cite_note-Urquhart-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-BTO_3-0" class="reference"><a href="Saxicola_rubetra#cite_note-BTO-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
<div id="toctitle">
